<DOC><DOCNO> AP880217-0089 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-88 0926EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Clash     02-17 0236</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Clash,0243</SECOND><HEAD>South Lebanon Clash Kills 17</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem guerrillasand pro-Israeli militiamen fought for six hours in south Lebanontoday, leaving at least 17 fighters dead and four wounded.   A police spokesman said the two sides used rockets, mortars, andautomatic rifles in the clash south of the Christian town ofJezzine, 10 miles east of the port city of Sidon.   He said seven fighters of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Armymilitia were killed and four wounded when Shiite Moslem guerillasof the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, ambushed theirpatrol at 6 a.m. outside Jezzine.   The South Lebanon Army ``sent reinforcements to the area andfought a six-hour battle killing 10 attackers,'' said thespokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity according toregulations.   He said that after the killing of its fighters, Hezbollahpounded the battle scene, two miles southeast of Jezzine, withmortar fire. It later recovered the bodies of six of its men.   The South Lebanon Army is based in a six-mile deepIsraeli-occupied border strip in south Lebanon and carries outfrequent patrols into Jezzine, a Christian town outside the zone.   Israel established the so-called security zone along the borderafter the withdrawal of the bulk of its occupation army from southLebanon in 1985, three years after it invaded the country.   Hezbollah comprises Shiite zealots, who are backed by Iran'sIslamic revolution.</TEXT></DOC>